Sons were born to David at Hebron: his eldest was Amnon, son of
Ahinoam the Jezreelitess; 
his second was Chileab, son of Abigail who had been the wife of
Nabal the Karmelite; his third was Absalom, son of Maakah, the daughter of Talmai the king of Geshur; 
his fourth was Adonijah, son of Haggith; his fifth was
Shephatiah, son of Abital; 
and his sixth Ithream, son of Eglah . . . These were born to
David at Hebron.

In the house of Obed-edom the Gittite the Eternal's ark remained for three months, and the Eternal
blessed Obed-edom and all his household. 
Now when king David was told that the Eternal had blessed the household of Obed-edom and all that
belonged to him, on account of the ark of God, David went and brought the ark of God up from Obed-edom's house to David's burg joyfully; 
as soon as the bearers of the Eternal's ark had gone six steps, he sacrificed an ox and a fatling;

David whirled before the Eternal with all his might in the dance, wearing only a linen kilt round his
middle; 
this was how David and all the house of Israel brought up the Eternal's ark with shouts and blasts of
the trumpet.
